  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "metaphysics-expert",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "No — keep First/Second/Zeroth, renaming creates problems",
    "content": "**No. Keep First/Second/Zeroth.**\n\nThree problems with the proposed renaming:\n\n1. **\"Ultimate Reality\" for 第一实在 directly contradicts footnote 25.** The author explicitly warns that 第一实在 is a name for epistemic-practical priority, not an ontological claim. \"Ultimate\" in English carries exactly the ontological weight the author is trying to avoid -- it implies \"most real,\" \"final,\" \"fundamental.\" An English reader encountering \"Ultimate Reality\" for phenomena will assume the author is making the strong claim that phenomena are ontologically foundational, which is precisely what the author denies. This would be the single most damaging mistranslation in the collection.\n\n2. **\"Ultimate Reality\" for 第一实在 collides with 第〇实在.** The whole point of the system is that traditional metaphysics calls 第〇实在 \"ultimate reality\" (终极实在), but the author argues this is unreachable. If 第一实在 is *also* called \"Ultimate Reality,\" the reader will conflate the two -- destroying the crucial distinction between what traditional metaphysics considers ultimate (第〇) and what the author considers practically primary (第一).\n\n3. **\"Secondary\" for 第二实在 does imply derivative/lesser.** In English, \"secondary\" carries connotations of inferiority (secondary importance, secondary source, secondary character). \"Second\" is ordinal and neutral -- it simply means \"the one that comes after first.\" The author's 第二实在 is not inferior to 第一实在; it is the domain of all our concepts, models, and understanding. Calling it \"secondary\" subtly devalues it in a way the numbering system does not.\n\nThe original numbering is elegant precisely because it is neutral. First/Second/Zeroth are ordinal labels that the author can then *explain* rather than having the English words do philosophical work the author did not intend. The translator's notes should clarify the roles; the terms themselves should stay clean.\n"
  }
}
